data.content:
Yes — **MSTest 3.4+** introduced a generic `DynamicData<T1, T2, …>` attribute that gives you compile-time type safety using tuples instead of `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key changes:**
- `DynamicData` → `DynamicData<string, bool>` — type parameters match your test method signature
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — value tuples instead of object arrays
- No more silent runtime casting errors; mismatched types fail at compile time

Requires the `Microsoft.Testing.Framework` package (MSTest 3.4+).
